<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Marchers called Sun a “fong kong” and told him to “go back to China”.Sun is a born South African of Chinese descent.The crowd, as well as an official who accepted the memorandum, did not give Sun a chance to speak. He stood in silence as more offensive slurs were thrown at him, while South African Communist Party (SACP) secretary-general Blade Nzimande looked on, along with other leaders, and did nothing to intervene.The crowd also mimicked sounds made in Kung Fu movies during fights.When Sun was signing the memorandum, some in the crowd shouted that he should not sign in Chinese.They also said Mashaba had sent Sun - whom a Cosatu official referred to as “Mr Lee” – because he was scared of workers and had therefore sent someone who knew karate.They called Mashaba a sellout. Mashaba threatened to take the organisations to the South African Human Rights Commission (SAHRC) if they did not apologise by Sunday.Cosatu came out on Tuesday morning, apologising for any embarrassment and hurt caused by the derogatory statements.“Cosatu will never condone any form of racism or racial discrimination. We have concluded that the statements made against Michael Sun were intolerant, patronising and hurtful and could be easily interpreted as bigoted. That is not what our organisation stands for,” read a statement.The SACP has not yet issued an apology.